pr_title: Python agent performance enhancement with asyncio
pr_body:
<!--
    ‚ö†Ô∏è Please make sure to read this template first, pull requests that don't accord with this template
    maybe closed without notice.
    Texts surrounded by `<` and `>` are meant to be replaced by you, e.g. <framework name>, <issue number>.
    Put an `x` in the `[ ]` to mark the item as CHECKED. `[x]`
-->

> This is a GSOC 2023 project Pull Request. Related issue: [issues#10408](https://github.com/apache/skywalking/issues/10408)

This PR is to improve the performance of the Python agent by using `asyncio coroutine` to replace the `threading` module in the communication between the agent and the OAP server.

- [x] Add a benchmark for the improvement, using [wrk](https://github.com/wg/wrk) to pressure testing the network throughput of the Python agents in a [FastAPI](https://github.com/tiangolo/fastapi) application.
- [x] The benchmark result üëá.

> `sync` is the original version, `async` is the improved version.

### gRPC

_sync_

![image.png](https://s2.loli.net/2023/07/07/TAshI5GaK28FxDE.png)

_async_

![image.png](https://s2.loli.net/2023/07/07/uhn9Vje84DfYHQO.png)

### HTTP

_sync_

![image.png](https://s2.loli.net/2023/07/07/jX4vGh6iMkAQmYz.png)

_async_

![image.png](https://s2.loli.net/2023/07/07/DbxIfsTG4Pj1OFi.png)

### Kafka

_sync_

![image.png](https://s2.loli.net/2023/07/07/QfCS9GI75ozmg6A.png)

_async_

![image.png](https://s2.loli.net/2023/07/07/HwOmQFdfgri4VaA.png)

- [x] Closes: https://github.com/apache/skywalking/issues/10408
- [x] Update the [`CHANGELOG.md`](https://github.com/apache/skywalking-python/blob/master/CHANGELOG.md).

Also in your code imports uvloop even if not enabled.', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2023, 8, 18, 19, 9, 38, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'Superskyyy', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 1298776420, 'comment_body': 'See previous comment', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2023, 8, 18, 19, 9, 51, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'Superskyyy', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 1298783774, 'comment_body': 'Is it any faster etc.? If so you could add a check to use to_thread. check if asyncio hasattr to_thread', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2023, 8, 18, 19, 19, 35, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'Superskyyy', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 1299186958, 'comment_body': '`asyncio.to_thread()` actually simply calls the pre-python 3.9 function `loop.run_in_executor()`, which uses `concurrent.futures.Executor` to create a thread pool to manage additional threads to execute specific coroutines. And here I simply use `Thread()` to create a new thread to execute the coroutine. Considering that we only need one extra thread to maintain the `eventloop`, the performance gap between the two should be negligible. In addition, `to_thread()`/`run_in_executor()` is an async function, which cannot actually be called here, and other codes need to be changed to achieve the same function as here. I write this comment mainly because I think `to_thread()` can make the code more concise and intuitive, but in fact it may not be necessary to use it at all. I will consider removing this comment in future changes.', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2023, 8, 19, 13, 30, 5, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'FAWC438', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 1302022438, 'comment_body': '```suggestion ## Performance improvement ```', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2023, 8, 22, 18, 18, 10, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'Superskyyy', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 1302022980, 'comment_body': '```suggestion We use [wrk](https://github.com/wg/wrk) to pressure test the network throughput of the Python agents in a [FastAPI](https://github.com/tiangolo/fastapi) application. ```', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2023, 8, 22, 18, 18, 37, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'Superskyyy', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 1302024635, 'comment_body': '```suggestion Asynchronous enhancements involve many code changes and introduced some new dependencies.
